CVE-2026-42198 (GHSA-98qh-xjc8-98pq, HIGH): pgjdbc's SCRAM-SHA-256 handshake derives
the PBKDF2 key from a server-supplied, unbounded iteration count, allowing a malicious
or impersonated PostgreSQL endpoint to peg a CPU core (DoS). Fixed in org.postgresql:postgresql 42.7.11.
CVE-2026-6860 (GHSA-3g76-f9xq-8vp6, MEDIUM): vert.x caches one SslContext per SNI name
without eviction, so an attacker can exhaust the heap with distinct ClientHello SNI values
(DoS). Fixed in the io.vertx 4.5.x line at 4.5.27.
Nessie's gradle/libs.versions.toml and the Quarkus platform BOM resolve these to vulnerable
versions (postgresql 42.7.10, vert.x 4.5.26) in the fast-jar packaging, so force the resolved
jars to the fixed versions. Applied after the jackson, netty, and opentelemetry force patches,
which edit the same build.gradle.kts region.

postgresql advisory: https://github.com/pgjdbc/pgjdbc/security/advisories/GHSA-98qh-xjc8-98pq
vert.x advisory: https://github.com/eclipse-vertx/vert.x/security/advisories/GHSA-3g76-f9xq-8vp6
vert.x 4.5.27 release: https://github.com/eclipse-vertx/vert.x/releases/tag/4.5.27

